# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1876-major-league-baseball-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1876-major-league-baseball-season/1875-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1875 throughout the world.
[src:1876-major-league-baseball-season/1876-boston-red-caps-season] The **1876 Boston Red Caps season** was the sixth season of the franchise.
[src:1876-major-league-baseball-season/1876-boston-red-caps-season] With the dissolution of the National Association, the Boston team joined the brand new National League.
[src:1876-major-league-baseball-season/1876-boston-red-caps-season] The team name was changed from the Boston Red Stockings to the **Boston Red Caps** to avoid confusion with the new Cincinnati Red Stockings team.
[src:1876-major-league-baseball-season/1876-boston-red-caps-season] Some of the players from the previous year's team defected to other ballclubs, so the team finished further down in the standings this season.
[src:1876-major-league-baseball-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1876 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fifth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National League and the third at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1876-major-league-baseball-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings, as one of the founding members of the new National League, won the NL's initial championship during this season with a record of 52–14.
[src:1876-major-league-baseball-season/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] The **1876 Cincinnati Reds season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1876-major-league-baseball-season/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] It was the team's first season of existence, having been formed as part of the brand new National League in 1876.
[src:1876-major-league-baseball-season/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] This team was not related (except by name) to the previous Cincinnati Red Stockings National Association team, which had folded in 1870.
[src:1876-major-league-baseball-season/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] One bright spot for the Reds was the play of Charley Jones, who led the club with a batting average of .286, had the second highest home run total in the league with four, and was among the league leaders in doubles and slugging percentage.
[src:1876-major-league-baseball-season/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds played their first ever game on April 25, 1876, defeating the St.
[src:1876-major-league-baseball-season/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] Louis Brown Stockings 2–1 at Avenue Grounds.
[src:1876-major-league-baseball-season/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] Wins would be few and far between for the Reds, as after putting up a solid 3–2 record in their opening five games, the Reds would go on an eleven-game losing streak to fall to 3–13.
[src:1876-major-league-baseball-season/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] After defeating the Hartford Dark Blues 8–2 to end their losing streak, the Reds would then have a thirteen-game losing streak, and saw their record fall to 4–26.
[src:1876-major-league-baseball-season/1876-cincinnati-reds-season] By the time the season was finished, Cincinnati had the worst record in the National League, as they ended the season with a 9–56 record, 42.5 games behind the first place Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1876-major-league-baseball-season/1876-hartford-dark-blues-season] The **Hartford Dark Blues** joined the new National League for its first season in 1876, and team owner Morgan Bulkeley was the first National League president.
[src:1876-major-league-baseball-season/1876-hartford-dark-blues-season] They finished the season in second place.
[src:1876-major-league-baseball-season/1876-louisville-grays-season] The **Louisville Grays** were formed prior to the 1876 Major League Baseball season and joined the just formed National League as a charter member.
[src:1876-major-league-baseball-season/1876-louisville-grays-season] They finished in fifth place in their debut season under manager Jack Chapman.
[src:1876-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The **1876 major league baseball season** was contested from April 22 through October 21, 1876, and saw the Chicago White Stockings as the pennant winner of the inaugural season of the National League and of Major League baseball.
[src:1876-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Two non-NA teams would join as charter members, including the Cincinnati Reds (unrelated to the modern team) and Louisville Grays.
[src:1876-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The 1876 schedule was formatted so that each team would play up to 10 games against each team in the league (split evenly between home and away games), for a maximum of 70 games (only fulfilled by the Boston Red Caps).
[src:1876-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Any game played against a team at home must be played within two months' time away, "under penalty of forfeiture." This was the only season that the National League adopted this format.
[src:1876-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see a more regulated format, requiring teams to schedule 12 games against each team.
[src:1876-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 22 featuring a game between the Boston Red Caps and Athletics of Philadelphia.
[src:1876-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on October 21, featuring a game between the Hartford Dark Blues and Boston Red Caps.
[src:1876-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The first doubleheader in major league history occurred on September 9 between the Cincinnati Reds and Hartford Dark Blues.
[src:1876-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The year ended with the first postseason competition in major league history.
[src:1876-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The contest featured the first and second-place regular season finishers.
[src:1876-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Three tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind occurred throughout the season (though standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:1876-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The Louisville Grays had three tie games.
[src:1876-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The Hartford Dark Blues, New York Mutuals, and Philadelphia Athletics had one tie game each.
[src:1876-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The Hartford Dark Blues would play their final game at the Hartford Ball Club Grounds on September 16 against the St.
[src:1876-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings, relocating to Brooklyn, New York at the Union Grounds as the Brooklyn Hartfords for the start of the 1877 season.
[src:1876-major-league-baseball-season/1876-new-york-mutuals-season] The **1876 New York Mutuals** concluded their sole season in the National League with a 21–35 win-loss record, placing them sixth in the standings.
